-------------------------------------------------Q/A-------------------------------------------------------
1-How does Fan Out service Work when a celebrity has 50 M followers?

Problem: Fanout-on-write means writing to 50M timeline caches on every tweet — this is called the 'hotkey' or 'celebrity problem'.

Solution — Hybrid Fanout:
• Normal users (<10K followers) → Fanout on Write (pre-compute timelines in Redis)
• Celebrities (>1M followers) → Fanout on Read (compute at query time)
• On timeline request, merge: pre-built feed + lazy-loaded celebrity tweets

Implementation: Tag celebrity accounts in User DB. Fanout service checks follower count before deciding strategy.
Where to improve
Add a follower-count threshold config (not hardcoded). Use a separate Celeb Tweet Cache with TTL so reads don't always hit DB. Consider ML-based thresholding based on engagement rate, not just follower count.

2- How would you handle 100000 tweets per second at peak?

Write path optimizations:
• Kafka partitioning by user_id — parallel consumption across consumers
• Cassandra for Tweet DB — designed for high write throughput, LSM tree storage
• Write-behind caching: write to Redis first, async flush to DB
• Shard API Gateway and Load Balancer horizontally

Numbers: Twitter's actual peak is ~6,000 TPS. 100K TPS needs ~17x more capacity — achievable with horizontal pod autoscaling (HPA) in Kubernetes.
Where to improve
Implement backpressure mechanisms in Kafka consumers. Use CQRS (Command Query Responsibility Segregation) — separate write model from read model. Add circuit breakers between services.

3-Why Cassandra for tweets instead of PostgreSQL?

Cassandra wins on:
• Write throughput: LSM-tree structure — appends only, no random I/O
• Horizontal scaling: consistent hashing, no master node
• High availability: tunable consistency (AP in CAP theorem)
• Time-series data fits naturally (tweet_id as partition key)

PostgreSQL wins on:
• Complex joins (not needed for tweets)
• Strong ACID transactions
• Relational integrity

Verdict: Tweets are write-heavy, append-only, never updated — perfect Cassandra use case.
Where to improve
Use Snowflake IDs (Twitter's actual approach) for tweet_id — encodes timestamp + machine_id + sequence. Enables time-range queries without secondary indexes.

4-Expalin Message Queue in Detail--Why Kafka specifically?

Kafka advantages over RabbitMQ:
• Log-based: messages retained on disk, consumers can replay
• Partitioning: parallel processing across consumer groups
• Throughput: millions of messages/sec per broker
• Ordering: guaranteed within a partition

Tweet flow through Kafka:
1. Tweet CRUD Service → produces to 'tweets' topic
2. Fanout consumers read from partition assigned to their user shard
3. Search indexer consumes same topic (separate consumer group)
4. Analytics service also consumes — zero coupling

Key config: replication factor = 3, min.insync.replicas = 2
Where to improve
Use Kafka Streams for real-time tweet analytics (trending topics). Implement dead-letter queues for failed fanout events. Add schema registry (Confluent) to enforce Avro schemas.

5-How does timeLine Cache work? what's stored in Redis?
Structure: Sorted Set per user
• Key: timeline:{user_id}
• Value: tweet_id (as member)
• Score: timestamp (enables time-range pagination)

Read flow:
1. Timeline Service: ZREVRANGE timeline:user123 0 19 (latest 20 tweets)
2. Fetch tweet content from Tweet Content DB by IDs
3. Merge with real-time celebrity tweets (hybrid fanout)

Write flow (Fanout Service):
ZADD timeline:{follower_id} {timestamp} {tweet_id}
ZREMRANGEBYRANK timeline:{follower_id} 0 -801 (keep last 800)
Where to improve
Add TTL per timeline key (7 days of inactivity → evict). Use Redis Cluster with consistent hashing. Add a Lua script for atomic ZADD + TRIM to avoid race conditions.

6-how does CDC( Change Data Capture) work b/w reply service and other service?
Tool: Debezium + Kafka

How it works:
1. Debezium connects to Replies DB as a replica
2. Reads PostgreSQL WAL (Write-Ahead Log) — the change stream
3. Converts each INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE into a Kafka event
4. Downstream services consume these events

Why not direct DB polling?
• Polling creates DB load and has latency
• CDC is event-driven — zero polling overhead
• Guaranteed ordering within a table partition

Use cases: Update reply counts on tweets, invalidate caches, sync to Elasticsearch
Where to improve
Use Outbox Pattern instead of direct CDC for transactional safety. Combine CDC with event sourcing for full audit trail. Add exactly-once semantics via Kafka transactions.

7-How Would you shard the tweet Content Database?

Strategy: Consistent Hashing on user_id
• All tweets by a user on same shard → efficient user timeline queries
• Shard key: user_id % num_shards

Problem with hot users: Celebrity on one shard = hotspot
Fix: Virtual nodes — celebrities get multiple virtual shards

Alternative: tweet_id sharding
• Distributes writes evenly
• But 'get all tweets by user' needs scatter-gather across all shards

Twitter's actual approach: Sharded MySQL (FlockDB for social graph) + Snowflake for IDs
Where to improve
Add shard rebalancing strategy using consistent hashing ring. Implement cross-shard query federation layer. Consider NewSQL databases (CockroachDB) that handle sharding automatically.

8- what is CAP theorem tradeOff in the system?
CAP Theorem: A distributed system can only guarantee 2 of: Consistency, Availability, Partition Tolerance

Different services, different choices:
• Tweet CRUD (Cassandra): AP — Available + Partition Tolerant. Eventual consistency is fine (slightly stale feed is OK)
• Auth & IAM: CP — Consistent + Partition Tolerant. Must never allow stale auth tokens
• Payment (if any): CP — Strong consistency required
• Search (Elasticsearch): AP — Eventual index updates are acceptable

Key interview phrase: 'We choose availability over consistency for read-heavy social features, but consistency for security-critical paths'
Where to improve
Document consistency guarantees per service in a 'consistency contract'. Use vector clocks or CRDTs for conflict resolution in distributed tweet storage.

9- How would you prevent DDos Attack on API gateway?
Layer 3/4 (Network level):
• AWS Shield / Cloudflare to absorb volumetric attacks
• IP allowlisting for admin endpoints

Layer 7 (Application level) — API Gateway:
• Rate limiting: 100 req/min per user_id, 1000 req/min per IP
• Token bucket or sliding window algorithm
• Geo-blocking for suspicious traffic patterns

CDN as first line of defense:
• Cache static content at edge — origin never sees the request
• Cloudflare WAF (Web Application Firewall)

Bot detection:
• CAPTCHA on auth endpoints
• Device fingerprinting
• Anomaly detection (ML-based)
Where to improve
Add API Gateway response caching to reduce backend load. Implement adaptive rate limiting (tighten limits when system is stressed). Add canary analysis to detect abnormal traffic patterns early.






















